04809nam a22007935i 9780812204216DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102004pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979580595  a97808122042167 a10.9783/97808122042162doi  a(DE-B1597)449284  a(OCoLC)759158191  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0030002bisacsh04a306.2/09731 aBoyte, Harry C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEveryday Politics :bReconnecting Citizens and Public Life /cHarry C. Boyte. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2010] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Developing a Theory and Practice of Everyday Politics -- t1. The Stirrings of a New Politics -- t2. Populisms -- t3. The Growth of Everyday Politics -- t4. Citizenship as Public Work -- t5. Citizen Education as a Craft, Not a Program -- t6. The Jane Addams School for Democracy -- t7. Professions as Public Work -- t8. "Architects of Democracy" -- t9. Spreading Everyday Politics -- t10. Freedom -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIncreasingly a spectator sport, electoral politics have become bitterly polarized by professional consultants and lobbyists and have been boiled down to the distributive mantra of "who gets what." In Everyday Politics, Harry Boyte transcends partisan politics to offer an alternative. He demonstrates how community-rooted activities reconnect citizens to engaged, responsible public life, and not just on election day but throughout the year. Boyte demonstrates that this type of activism has a rich history and strong philosophical foundation. It rests on the stubborn faith that the talents and insights of ordinary citizens—from nursery school to nursing home—are crucial elements in public life.Drawing on concrete examples of successful public work projects accomplished by diverse groups of people across the nation, Boyte demonstrates how citizens can master essential political skills, such as understanding issues in public terms, mapping complex issues of institutional power to create alliances, raising funds, communicating, and negotiating across lines of difference. He describes how these skills can be used to address the larger challenges of our time, thereby advancing a renewed vision of democratic society and freedom in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCivil societyzUnited States. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 0aPolitical participationzUnited States. 0aPower (Social sciences)zUnited States. 4aPolitical Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civics & Citizenship.2bisacsh  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Law & Political Sciencez978311041352608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220421640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812204216423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812204216.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041352-6  Penn Press eBook Package Law & Political Science  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13E